Short Title: Various Revenue Laws Changes. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
March 26, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MAKE VARIOUS TECHNICAL, CLARIFYING, AND ADMINISTRATIVE
3 CHANGES TO THE REVENUE LAWS; TO CONFORM TO THE FEDERAL SYSTEM
4 FOR AUDITING PARTNERSHIPS BY IMPOSING TAX AT THE PARTNERSHIP
5 LEVEL FOR FEDERAL CHANGES AND BY AUTHORIZING REFUNDS FOR
6 FEDERAL CHANGES; TO PROVIDE TAX PARITY FOR SHORT-TERM CAR
7 RENTALS BY EXPANDING ALTERNATE HIGHWAY USE TAX TO INCLUDE
8 PEER-TO-PEER RENTALS; TO SHIFT ENFORCEMENT OF VAPOR DIRECTORY
9 VIOLATIONS TO THE ALE DIVISION; AND TO ENHANCE TAX FORECLOSURE
10 AND SPECIAL ASSESSMENT COLLECTION EFFORTS.
11 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
12
13 PART I. PERSONAL INCOME TAX CHANGES
14 SECTION 1.1.(a) G.S. 105-153.5(c1) reads as rewritten:
15 "(c1) Other Additions. Adjustments. – The following other adjustments shall be made in
16 determining North Carolina taxable income:
17 (1) S Corporations subject to the provisions of Part 1A of this Article, partnerships
18 subject to the provisions of this Part, and estates and trusts subject to the
19 provisions of Part 3 of this Article must add any amount deducted under
20 section 164 of the Code as state, local, or foreign income tax.
21 (2) A shareholder of an S Corporation subject to the provisions of Part 1A of this
22 Article may deduct the aggregate amount of losses or deductions of an S
23 Corporation pursuant to the provisions of G.S. 105-131.4.
24 (3) A shareholder of an S Corporation subject to the provisions of Part 1A of this
25 Article must add the aggregate amount of losses or deductions of an S
26 Corporation included in the shareholder's adjusted gross income to the extent
27 the losses or deductions exceed the shareholder's combined adjusted bases,
28 determined in accordance with G.S. 105-131.3, in the stock and indebtedness
29 of the S Corporation."
30 SECTION 1.1.(b) This section is effective for taxable years beginning on or after
31 January 1, 2025.
32 SECTION 1.2.(a) G.S. 105-153.5A reads as rewritten:
33 "§ 105-153.5A. Net operating loss provisions.
34 …
35 (g) Limitation. – The provisions of this section apply only to individuals, estates, and
36 trusts."
*S595-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 1.2.(b) G.S. 105-153.5A(a) reads as rewritten:
2 "(a) State Net Operating Loss. – A taxpayer's State net operating loss for a taxable year is
3 the amount by which business deductions for the year exceed gross income for the year as
4 determined under the Code adjusted as provided in G.S. 105-153.5 and G.S. 105-153.6. The
5 amount of a taxpayer's State net operating loss must also be determined in accordance with the
6 following modifications:
7 (1) No State net operating loss deduction shall be allowed.
8 (2) The amount deductible on account of losses from sales or exchanges of capital
9 assets shall not exceed the amount includable on account of gains from sales
10 or exchanges of capital assets.
11 (3) The exclusion provided by Code section 1202 shall not be allowed.
12 (4) No deduction shall be allowed under G.S. 105-153.5(a1) for the child
13 deduction.
14 (5) The deductions which are not attributable to a taxpayer's trade or business
15 shall be allowed only to the extent of the amount of the gross income not
16 derived from such trade or business.
17 (6) Any deduction under Code section 199A shall not be allowed.
18 (7) The amount of the taxpayer's excess business loss, as defined under the
19 provisions of section 461(l) of the Code, shall be fully allowed as a State net
20 operating loss."
21 SECTION 1.2.(c) Subsection (a) of this section is effective when this Part becomes
22 law and applies retroactively to taxable years beginning on or after January 1, 2022. Subsection
23 (b) of this section is effective for taxable years beginning on or after January 1, 2025. The
24 remainder of this section is effective when this Part becomes law.
25 SECTION 1.3.(a) G.S. 105-160.2 reads as rewritten:
26 "§ 105-160.2. Imposition of tax.
27 (a) Scope. – The tax imposed by this Part applies to the taxable income of estates and
28 trusts as determined under the provisions of the Code except as otherwise provided in this Part.
29 The taxable income of an estate or trust is the same as taxable income for such an estate or trust
30 under the provisions of the Code, adjusted as provided in G.S. 105-153.5 and G.S. 105-153.6,
31 except that the adjustments provided in G.S. 105-153.5 and G.S. 105-153.6 are apportioned
32 between the estate or trust and the beneficiaries based on the distributions made during the
33 taxable year. G.S. 105-153.6.
34 (b) Tax Base. – The tax is computed on the amount of the taxable income of the estate or
35 trust that is for the benefit of a resident of this State, or for the benefit of a nonresident to the
36 extent that the income (i) is derived from North Carolina sources and is attributable to the
37 ownership of any interest in real or tangible personal property in this State or (ii) is derived from
38 a business, trade, profession, or occupation carried on in this State. For purposes of the preceding
39 sentence, taxable income and gross income is computed subject to the adjustments provided in
40 G.S. 105-153.5 and G.S. 105-153.6. G.S. 105-153.6 and is apportioned and allocated to this State
41 under G.S. 105-130.4.
42 (c) Tax Rate. – The tax on the amount computed above is at the rate levied in
43 G.S. 105-153.7. The fiduciary responsible for administering the estate or trust shall pay the tax
44 computed under the provisions of this Part.
45 (d) Adjustments. – For the purposes of this section, the adjustments provided in
46 G.S. 105-153.5 and G.S. 105-153.6 are apportioned between the estate or trust and the
47 beneficiaries based on the distributions made during the taxable year."
48 SECTION 1.3.(b) This section is effective for taxable years beginning on or after
49 January 1, 2025.
50 SECTION 1.4. G.S. 105-163.6 reads as rewritten:
51 "§ 105-163.6. When employer must file returns and pay withheld taxes.
Page 2 Senate Bill 595-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 …
2 (c) Monthly. – An employer who withholds an average of at least two hundred fifty
3 dollars ($250.00) but less than two thousand dollars ($2,000) of State income taxes from wages
4 each month must file a return and pay the withheld taxes on a monthly basis. A return for the
5 months of January through November is due by the 15th day of the month following the end of
6 the month covered by the return. A return for the month of December is due the following January
7 31.
8 (d) Semiweekly. – An employer who withholds an average of at least two thousand
9 dollars ($2,000) of State income taxes from wages each month shall must file a return by the date
10 set under the Code for filing a return for federal employment taxes attributable to the same wages
11 and shall on a quarterly basis. A quarterly return covers a calendar quarter and is due by the last
12 day of the month following the end of the quarter. The employer also must pay the withheld State
13 taxes by the date set under the Code for depositing or paying federal employment taxes
14 attributable to the same wages. The date set by the Code for depositing or paying federal
15 employment taxes shall be determined without regard to § 6302(g) of the Code.
16 An extension of time granted to file a return for federal employment taxes attributable to
17 wages is an automatic extension of time for filing a return for State income taxes withheld from
18 the same wages, and an extension of time granted to pay federal employment taxes attributable
19 to wages is an automatic extension of time for paying State income taxes withheld from the same
20 wages. An employer who pays withheld State income taxes under this subsection is not subject
21 to interest on or penalties for a shortfall in the amount due if the employer would not be subject
22 to a failure-to-deposit penalty had the shortfall occurred in a deposit of federal employment taxes
23 attributable to the same wages and the employer pays the shortfall by the date the employer would
24 have to deposit a shortfall in the federal employment taxes.forth below:
25 (1) If an employer's payday falls on a Wednesday, Thursday, or Friday, the
26 withheld taxes must be paid on or before the following Wednesday.
27 (2) If an employer's payday falls on a Saturday, Sunday, Monday, or Tuesday, the
28 withheld taxes must be paid on or before the following Friday.
29 (3) If any of the three weekdays following the close of a semiweekly period is a
30 legal holiday, the employer has an additional business day for each day that is
31 a legal holiday by which to pay the withheld taxes.
32 …
33 (f) The Secretary may close a taxpayer's withholding account if the taxpayer files no
34 withholding returns or files returns showing no State income taxes withheld for a period of 18
35 months."
